{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491485"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:48:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:48:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"953"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/953"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.13,0.7,0.03,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"953"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105832"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/953"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"953"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88301"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"583"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2103"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2111"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42178"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105832"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a two month history of fatigue and generalised weakness. She reports no changes in weight, shortness of breath, chest pain, muscles or joint pain, sweating, and does not report feeling more anxious lately. Her medical history is unremarkable. She is not on any medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she appears well. Her blood pressure is 168/104mmHg, pulse rate 96/min and respiratory rate 12/min. She has no bruising or skin changes, and is of a normal body habitus. Initial bloods show she has a potassium of 2.8 mmol/L (3.5 \u2013 4.9). An ECG is unremarkable. She is referred to an endocrinologist for further work-up.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate test to confirm the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urinary metanephrines","Overnight dexamethasone suppression test","Plasma aldosterone/renin ratio","MRI of pituitary gland","Blood sugar and ketone level"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary aldosteronism\u003C/strong\u003E (previously known as Conn\u0027s syndrome) is the most likely diagnosis in this women given her fatigue, weakness, hypertension, and hypokalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eplasma aldosterone/renin ratio\u003C/strong\u003E is the initial investigation required for diagnosis of primary aldosteronism, as it has high sensitivity, but low specificity. This test has specific protocols around timing, body position, and collection; thus, is most commonly performed in a specialist setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary metanephrines\u003C/strong\u003E are useful in the diagnosis of pheochromocytoma, which usually presents with hypertension, anxiety, sweating and palpitations due to excess adrenaline release. Given this patient does not have any of these symptoms, pheochromocytoma is a less likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvernight dexamethasone suppression test \u003C/strong\u003Eis used to diagnose Cushing\u0027s syndrome; a syndrome characterised by increased cortisol. Cushing\u0027s syndrome has different causes; such as exogenous steroid use, ACTH secreting pituitary tumour (known as Cushing\u0027s disease), or an adrenal adenoma. Cushing\u0027s syndrome is characterised by weight gain, thinning of skin, striae, and bruising. Although Cushing\u0027s syndrome can also cause fatigue, muscle weakness, and hypokalaemia, as seen in this patient, given the lack of other symptoms, this is not the most likely cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, an \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI of the pituitary\u003C/strong\u003E can diagnose a pituitary adenoma which may be causing Cushing\u0027s disease; however, this would be an inappropriate next diagnostic test unless there was a high clinical suspicion (e.g. symptoms and signs consistent with Cushing\u0027s syndrome and a bitemporal hemianopia visual defect suggesting a pituitary adenoma)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood sugar and ketone level \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be performed in patients with suspected diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA). DKA presents acutely with severe dehydration, thirst, polyuria, and confusion, and is not a likely differential in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurther testing: \u003C/strong\u003EFollowing a plasma aldosterone/renin ratio, a definitive diagnosis can be obtained from a saline suppression test. A CT abdomen should then be performed to see if the cause is an adrenal adenoma. If there is an adenoma, adrenal vein sampling should be performed to confirm the adenoma is secreting aldosterone prior to possible adrenalectomy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Plasma aldosterone/renin ratio is the first test used to evaluate patients with a clinical suspicion of primary aldosteronism (Conn\u0027s syndrome)."],"references":["Schirpenbach C, Reincke M. Primary aldosteronism: Current knowledge and controversies in Conn\u0027s syndrome. Nat Clin Pract Endocrinol Metab. 2007;3(3):220-7.  Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17315030/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88301"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"953"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88301"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-14T09:57:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-14T09:57:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"953"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105832"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"